                We typically label angles by the Greek letter \( \theta \),
                pronounced "theta."
                Once we have singled out a particular angle,
                each side has a new name:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    A is the <strong>opposite</strong> of \( \theta \).
                </li>
                <li>
                    B is the <strong>adjacent</strong> of \( \theta \).
                </li>
                <li>
                    C is the <strong>hypotenuse</strong>.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
        <div class = 'col-md-6'>
            <ul>
                <li class = 'm-1'>
                    \( \sin \theta = \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{hypotenuse}} \)
                </li>
                <li class = 'm-1'>
                    \( \cos \theta = \frac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{hypotenuse}} \)
                </li>
                <li class = 'm-1'>
                    \( \tan \theta = \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{adjacent}} \)
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class = 'col-md-6'>
            <p>
                Whenever we know what an angle is, we can use the three <em>trigonometric functions</em>:
                the sine, the cosine, and the tangent.
                To remember these three formulas, we use the silly word "SOHCAHTOA,"
                which stands for:
                "Sine is opposite over hypotenuse; cosine is adjacent over hypotenuse; tangent is opposite over adjacent."
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

